>I think the only thing I would/can defend is that Jason needed to initiate the confession
My idea with that was that I wasn't sure what you want the main conflict to be, and in the first three chapters it looked like you were setting up for the big confession to be the climax. Right now it doesn't really have a main conflict.
Risk aversion isn't a good trait to write your protagonist around because it generally makes for a passive/reactive character instead of an active one. There's a lot of reasons why passive characters are undesirable, but I think it's a massive sin/misstep for romantic stories specifically because good relationships take hard work to build and maintain from both parties, and it feels like Jennifer is currently doing a lot of the heavy lifting.

Well this is awkward, looks like me and that other anon finished our reviews at the same time. Anyway, here's the review of chances I promised a few days ago.

>Chapter 1 Snapshot
General Thoughts: This was a good introduction to our main characters. Their most important traits are established, personalities are distinct, baseline relationship is set. It’s clear that despite being written in third person we’re seeing the story primarily from Jason’s perspective and that continues through chapter 4. Nothing wrong with that, but you may want to consider either including some of Jennifer’s inner thoughts or writing some scenes from her perspective so more depth can be added to her character. I know you do this a little towards the end of chapter 2 but I believe it would be intriguing to see more of her point of view as the relationship progresses, even after four chapters she still comes off as a generic tomboy childhood friend and this general is filled that specific archetype.

This might just be me being retarded, but when she brought out the polaroid camera and described it as new I thought that meant the time period of the story was in the 90s/80s since that’s around the last time instant cameras like that were popular. However, the beginning of the next chapter makes the setting more contemporary with them using a laptop and projector to stream movies. Maybe a context clue or two should have been added so the reader has a better idea of the time period?

>Chapter 2 Comfort
General thoughts: More slice of life. Last sentence of the first paragraph is cut off, you probably want to fix that. A major character conflict is introduced in Jason’s fear of getting too close to Jennifer, though I have to say you were too hasty in resolving this issue in the very next chapter since it leaves chapter 4 feeling aimless, I’ll expand on that later. Not much to say about this one, it’s mostly setup for the emotional payoff in chapter 3.
Anonymous
  • Post

Anonymous Sun 06 Feb 2022 04:08:07 No.45323867 Report
Quoted By: >>45323903
>>45323838
>Chapter 3 Reveals
General thoughts: Jennifer’s personality is expressed well in this chapter. I thought it was cute how she teased him to the point of confessing his feelings. I liked Nikki and her subtle attraction to Jason though I have to say I’m disappointed that she left as quickly as she came. I think seeing her and Jennifer passively aggressively butt heads would have made for a nice scene in the restaurant. The resolution at the end is satisfying.

>Chapter 4 Home
General thoughts: Alright, this is the chapter I have the most issues with. The first chapter set up our characters, the second introduced interpersonal conflict, the third resolved that conflict, and frankly I don’t know what the purpose of this fourth chapter is. It’s more slice of life but unlike the previous chapter I found no real draw to continue reading as I made my way through it. The relationship between the two seems stable, a minor external conflict is hinted at with Jennifer disliking Marcus but that plot point is never expanded upon, Jennifer brings up her father not liking humans but again that possible plot point is never fleshed out. I don’t see anything here other than their mundane interactions at the end of the day. It’s adding flavor to their relationship but personally I find flavor without substance to be a very boring thing. If it was your objective to write a comfy little chapter detailing their new life together than you have accomplished that wonderfully but if I were writing this, and I bet there’s a lot of people glad I’m not, I would introduce a new overarching conflict for our characters to overcome even if it means reducing the comfy factor. I don’t mean to imply the conflict has to be anything serious or life threatening, just important enough to keep the reader interested in what happens next.

This is just me but whenever I write a chapter out (or read someone else’s work) when I get to the end I often ask myself questions like “Well what was the point of this? How are the characters different at the end compared to the beginning? What are the revelations? Do the character’s feelings change? Is there any setup? Is there any payoff?” I like to see a clearly defined purpose to each chapter in regard to the story as a whole and I’m just not really getting that feeling here.

In addition, I feel that you’re stepping too hard on the gas when moving the timeline up. We’re going from them confessing their feelings for one another straight to them living together in an apartment. Fleshing out their relationship more with events in between those two milestones I feel would have been a more natural progression for the story.

Grammar: Minor typos were noticed throughout the series, nothing that stood out aside from that cut off sentence in chapter 2.

Suggestion: At an average chapter length of approximately 2,500 words I strongly recommend you make your chapters lengthier so that you have more time to flesh out characters, conflicts, and interactions.

TLDR: Very comfy so far, be wary of the difference between flavor and filler, keep it up

Anonymous Sun 06 Feb 2022 04:51:15 No.45324876 Report

>>45323931
>Dune
> reason?
Because Dune Messiah and Children of Dune require Dune as a background. Without reading these books, you then miss out on God Emperor of Dune, which is one of the masterworks of science fiction of all time.

>>45324084
>heard that the conflict was about multiple factions trying to control a planet and harness its resources,
It's all of that, and a good bit more.

Frank Herbert specifically wrote the theme about spice as a metaphor for limited resource depletion. At the time he used oil/petrochemicals and clean water as his model, then extrapolated something essential to an entire galaxy (and, technically, the entire universe).

However, spice is just the gateway drug to the Golden Path. I think you're going to enjoy it. Take your time and really absorb as much detail along the way as you can. Nearly every paragraph of Herbert's works are a Chekhov's Gun one way or another. Some go off in other books. I hope you enjoy it.
